Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow you to search among the stars for relatives, that is, those that emerged from the same cluster.
The results of their research were published in the journal Nature, and can be read briefly on the university’s website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas preceding the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, by its chemical composition it is possible to determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the related stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to the appearance of differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of the simulations carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, scientists used a supercomputer to model two streams of interstellar gas that together formed the cloud.
This object for several million years under the action of its own gravity is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added paint tags to the initial gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieves a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
