Recalling the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill that protects trade union organization as a civil right.
“Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs,” says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is a co-chair of the Progressive Faction Congress.
That's why I'm proud to introduce the Workers' Rights Act, along with the Civil Rights Movement symbol John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate against trade union organizations as it does with other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of trade union opponents.
The amendment of the Law on the Regulation of Labour Relations in such a way as to allow workers who face discrimination for participating in trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and fines - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis, and co-authors of the bill are proposing is to recall a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have been subjected to in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country – Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country at the same time defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hideki Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions play a role in the formation of a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to an organization, and to negotiations, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognising that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: “The right to form associations to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will not have legal force; measures aimed at these purposes will be found to be unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which would be adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the compilers included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and defend themselves”.
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions — and to have this union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — should be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As St. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions, the trade unions have miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it should be for us.
The official recognition of labour rights as human rights – and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against trade unions – has long been a thing of the past.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
A judge is temporarily blocking a law that could shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the introduction of Louisiana law, which his supporters say will likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginadel in June and was due to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to admit patients to hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that for the moment doctors can continue to perform legal abortions, continuing to seek such powers.
“The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to exercise their powers,” Judge John DeGrevells wrote in his ruling.
The hearing will take place during the month in which the judge will make a more permanent decision under this law.
Defenders of the right to abortion welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital powers.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” Nancy Nortap, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, said in a statement.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applies to doctors from two clinics who did not act as plaintiffs in the case, and also applied for admissions.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts have recently recognized such measures as unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would have closed most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that laws on admissions impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some also noted their positive effect in the closure of clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has the authority to be admitted to the hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admissions await a decision.
