Clearly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow to consolidate the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper because of subsidies from another state.
In other words, the struggle for the buyer will be between companies working under the same laws of the industry.
On the other hand, says Kasyanov, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of domestic needs of compatriots far from all articles.
And in this situation, the trade networks will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods to half the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that poor quality goods will enter the countertops.
It is possible that foreign products with broken labels will be delivered under the guise of manufactured in Russia,” the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that with such a schedule, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, as the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods can also affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to propel prices for the latter as a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, forgotten in the early 2000s, was talked about again by economists in February of this year due to the continuous devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the background of difficult relations with the West, the question of the refusal of imported products becomes even more relevant.
The law is designed to oblige retailers in the formation of orders to consider domestic manufacturers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the way of import substitution, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter period of time,” says Deputy Oleg Nilov.
A particularly effective quota mechanism would be for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example in the dairy sector, where the share of imports was 25 per cent.
Our farmers are really able to fully cover the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, a powerful pulse can also be obtained meat production.
As you know, the largest share of imports is kept on beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% still belongs to Russian products,” Kasyanov argues.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas on domestic products will facilitate import substitution and can speed up this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, because it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko believes.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported from abroad, which means that there will be no full import substitution, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
In addition, there is little to establish quotas, it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to meet these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees and will provide," the expert states.
Untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James posted a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who procrastinate in rural Australia face a higher risk of death from ovarian cancer than those who live in cities.
Researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research said the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher for those living in regions and remote areas of the state than for those living in urban areas.
NEBEST RESEARCH: New Medications May Slow Lung and Ovarian Cancers
The researchers followed the medical path of women for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that a woman’s age at the time of diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases, and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that a misdiagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that increasing the number of outbound services that would allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from their home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elise Nive, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
