Inflation has come out of the holiday.
Will the Russians feel a sharp rise in prices?
As a result of the cross-sanctions of Russia and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not fit into the forecasts of the authorities, VTB Capital analysts are convinced.
According to experts, the postponed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to inflation shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year and then less - 6.5%.
However, according to the newspaper Kommersant, this week the MER is expected to make “small but fundamental” adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency can lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected net zero growth in the population's income.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation are valid for a year - until August 2015.
How could such a high inflation be expected in such a situation?
The current situation implies a one-time shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change," a source in the Ministry of Finance said.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the government’s financial and economic bloc regarding inflation and forecast a price increase of 8% in 2014.
The main effect of the food bans will come along with the possible introduction of sales tax (SST) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
Inflation will peak at 9% in February, after which the annual rate of price growth will go down, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflation results after the Russian Federation introduced “careful sanctions”.
AiF.ru surveyed the experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, head of the analytical department of AForex FC:
Price increases are already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially significant products began to be valued, the government was forced to launch measures of systematic monitoring of price stability in order to prevent the risks of unjustified price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators so that the authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiates the price hike.
The key factors in the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the colossal rate of capital outflow, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to population flight into foreign currency, as well as the embargo on the import of food products from the countries that joined the anti-Russian movement.
If inflationary pressure remained under control, the basket value of the minimum set of products would not jump by 12% in a single quarter.
The ban on the import of food products provoked a shock of supply in the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final value.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the mechanism of import substitution, as well as increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market through domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry the risks of growth of the inflationary component.
If we add to this the fiscal reasons related to the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the deteriorating prospects for economic growth, by the end of this year inflation may well exceed 8%.
Alexander Razuvayev, director of the analytical department "Alpari"
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, at zero it was also above the current level, the other thing is that it was then compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think at the end of the year inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Plato Maguta, the asset manager of the Maguta Foundation
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is still successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector - this can lead to certain difficulties and increase inflationary expectations of the population, which are usually traditionally manifested in the purchase of cash in order to secure their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But the rise in prices traditionally begins after the summer solstice and may become more noticeable this fall.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to stand, as the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
Gardening centers are saddened by the decrease in the number of homeowners
Such a fall, due to an exceptional reduction in the number of homeowners under the age of 35, could lead to horticultural centers starting to lose tens of millions of pounds a year as today’s young consumers reach “the primary age of horticulture,” according to an HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to this report, homeowners spend an average of 55 percent of the amount that homeowners spend on gardening.
It mentions an increase in the number of people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting yards in front of a home for parking and a reduction in the size of the garden as other factors threatening the industry, whose annual sales are estimated at <0xC2><0xA3>5 billion.
In Greater London, where the number of homeowners has fallen from 61 percent to 43 percent in six years, the UK’s lowest rate of spending on gardening goods is on household goods.
