The biggest Chinese companies have joined forces against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China’s largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and internet giants Tencent Holdings (social networks, messengers, etc.) and Baidu (China’s largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online shopping market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left behind even its American rivals – eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
Union of the largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of it will belong to Wanda and 15% to each of the Internet companies, according to the Wanda Group.
Registration of the company is planned in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu’s search services with the popular social platform WeChat (China’s largest social network, with around 438 million users), Tencent, and Wanda’s infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial real estate properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) in the construction of a movie studio and theme park in Qingdao (a city in eastern China on the Yellow Sea coast).
It is expected that the project will attract more than 1 million visitors annually and bring a profit of $ 960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American network of cinemas AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest operator of cinemas in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all its shopping centers, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by Alibaba’s newly-created competitor.
According to Dong Tse, who will head the new company, thanks to the merger Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new platform is set to become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, Dong Tse said.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract buyers online so that they come to the usual offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon sales services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce,” said Wanda Wang Jianlin (Bloomberg).
"The current O2O site in China does not exist, and in this situation, the chances are approximately equal for everyone," he said.
China’s e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and McKinsey & Co. estimates its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, according to Bloomberg data official statistics: this is more than the population of any country in the world, except India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015, this number can grow to 850 million people.
Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huathen was China’s richest man until recently, however, according to Bloomberg’s millionaire index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already surpassed him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his share in Alibaba.
Baidu leader Robin Lee is now ranked third among China’s richest people, while Wanda’s Wang Jianglin is fourth in the ranking.
“It’s very interesting to watch this battle: the three richest people join forces to challenge the even richer,” said Bloomberg, director of China’s e-commerce research center in Hangzhou, China.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to be able to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after its creation: “Rome can’t be built in a day.”
The fact that Alibaba is not so easy to compete not only with new companies, but also well-deserved leaders of the world Internet trade, indicates a report published the day before on the financial indicators of Alibaba for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as something between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June the Chinese company earned more than both of its American competitors combined.
Alibaba's net profit for the period is almost twice the same as its competitors' combined profit - it grew almost three times year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has tremendous potential for generating money, largely through its mobile apps,” said a report by an analyst at Hong Kong’s Arete Research Service.
According to Alibaba’s updated prospectus on the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission’s website, the number of active mobile users of the company’s services in July was 188 million, significantly exceeding the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the past quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba will name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba’s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) could take place as early as September 16.
The company’s road show, which precedes this event, will start on September 3.
Alibaba’s IPO is expected to become a record in NYSE history and allow the company to attract around $20 billion.
So far, the record for the amount of funds raised on U.S. exchanges belonged to the Visa payment system, which in 2008 carried out the primary placement of its shares, earning $17.9 billion.
