Calculation of the estimate of construction sites in Russia will be carried out in a new way
The issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as the problem of connection to networks Federal Antimonopoly Service takes special control.
An expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector has been established at FAS.
At his meeting, the head of the management of control of residential, construction and natural resources FAS Vadim Solovyev said that "Today's calculation of the estimate of construction facilities is absolutely incomprehensible."
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to an unreasonable construction price, the FAS believes.
And offer the cost of construction of state-owned facilities at the design stage to determine based on market prices of constructive solutions instead of the currently applied estimated norms and unit prices for technological operations.
These proposals are included in the "road map" and are now under consideration in the ministry.
“The replacement of traditional estimated documentation in construction for the calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry,” explained Vadim Soloviev.
After all, now every bolt and nut is calculated in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes in the documentation unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors".
In the ministry with the FAS agree.
"The first developments on the transition to the calculation of the cost on the constructive elements are already there: methods for calculating the prices on the constructive solutions, compiling estimates on these indicators have been developed," said Elena Zhukova, head of the Department of Urban Planning and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction.
As a pilot, the field of road construction was chosen.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
Anatoly Demyanko, head of construction company Profi-Invest, told RGB, the estimated standards have long been outdated, but another mechanism for business has not yet been proposed.
“As for the proposed calculations on the structural elements, it is difficult to implement in practice, since completely different technologies are often used in the construction of buildings,” he believes.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely thanks to the state order.
According to the Chairman of the Board of the State Enterprise "Expert Community of State Order Professionals" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Deputy Director for Engineering of Rosatom’s Sectoral Center of Capital Construction Vladimir Malakhov noted that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to the portfolio of contracts, and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors in this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is protected as much as possible from someone’s controlling influence.
The expert council was asked to form a state order system in such a way that the same contractor is not entitled to receive more than one contract in the amount of more than 1 billion rubles or several contracts in the amount of more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As explained by Elena Zhukova, in this case it will be necessary to assign the customer with the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the number of employees of the customer and budget costs for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer’s specialists will have to have knowledge to assess the quality of the work performed by the contracting organizations, as well as their safety.
Often with such a breakdown, it will be necessary to determine who will be responsible for the safety of the object as a whole.
In addition, this approach can lead to the outflow of highly qualified public procurement participants due to the lack of interest in receiving a government order for the partial amount of work and a small amount of the contract.
Deputy heads of the expert-consultation center of the Procurement Institute Alexander Evstashenkov believes that now the state order procedure has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And he gave this example: "the participant when filling in the application must indicate "specific indicators" without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "should not be", "from", "more", "less", "similar", "or", "type", "not lower", "lower", "above", "may", "may", "may", "may" and "may"
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of the application submitted by contracting entities.
Another problem 44-FZ, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to evaluate the quality of work through the “paper” offer of the participant at the application stage.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to assess only the qualification of the contractor, but not the quality of the work, which has not yet begun to be carried out, - the expert believes.
The quality of the work can only be assessed when it is received.
The expert council was also asked to move the marginal income from the top to the bottom echelon in order to eliminate intermediate contractors.
Chairman of the expert council, Secretary of State, Deputy Head of FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this should not be done, since the contractor must be responsible for the order.
Otherwise, it will turn out, as in the famous reprise of Arkady Raikin "Atelier": "Is there a claim to the buttons?".
Israeli Children Return to School After the Gaza War
Thousands of Israeli children in territories near the Gaza Strip went back to school on Monday after spending a summer in bomb shelters when rockets and rain-throwing mines fell on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as riots raged.
The beginning of schooling brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-stricken settlements of southern Israel, but traces of fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the Pashos kindergarten, which was hit by the rocket, removed traces of fragments from the walls and playgrounds before the arrival of the students.
“We’re a little scared, but we’re looking forward to the future,” said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibutza Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to a measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was "a little weird" to start going to school again.
“It was a difficult time and we didn’t leave our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is located near the border with Gaza, to express his support.
Before the cease-fire agreement ended the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not take to the streets or leave their homes, leaving for safer areas further away from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the border with Gaza where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mine, doubt that they should go back.
The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families have not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the border with Gaza that was heavily ravaged by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study diligently and said, “We will do our best to give you knowledge and ensure your safety.”
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce on Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately put an end to the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand to lift the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and to open airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its weapons and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect negotiations is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians died in the war, including three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the United Nations.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; however, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed by the Israeli side.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
As a result of the Israeli attacks, thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip have been damaged and destroyed, and an estimated 250,000 people have found refuge in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
Because tens of thousands of people were still in shelters and fighting continued, officials in charge of education postponed the start of the school year last week.
“I hope the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and as Jewish children,” said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza’s schools.
