4 tips on how to achieve better quality underwater photos and videos
If you want to photograph or shoot videos underwater, you have a number of options for equipment.
The cheapest option is a water-resistant "washer", for example, the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or an action camera, for example, the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which sell for about $300.
I took these pictures on a family holiday with a few cameras, all for about $350.
No matter what equipment you use, a few rules must be followed in order to achieve the best results.
Check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the camera battery and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also, set up your camera for the type of photos or videos you’ll be shooting.
Some cameras and video cameras have shooting modes or object type that optimize exposure for darkened underwater conditions.
And before you jump into the water, figure out how deep your equipment can sink.
Some cameras are designed for only 5 feet, others - 50 or 60 feet.
Check out our buyer’s guide and digital camera ratings for both traditional and waterproof models.
Take a few pictures - because many of them will not work.
The soapboxes have LCDs that will help you compose photos, while the action cameras usually don’t.
Even if you have an LCD, it will be difficult to see under water, and the framing will be a random process.
So take a few shots.
Also, if your camera has a serial shooting mode that takes a few shots with slightly different exposure settings, use them.
Stay on the surface.
The amount of light is significantly reduced the deeper you dive under the water.
If possible, stay on the surface when shooting in a pool, river, or ocean.
It will also allow you to convey more color in the photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Get closer to the shooting targets.
This is great advice for shooting on land, but it’s even more important underwater because of the dim light conditions.
Especially important if you are shooting on an action camera: This equipment is often equipped with a fixed, wide-angle lens, which means that you will have to approach the shooting objects if you want to fill the shot.
