Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed.
The British woman said she had spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karen Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years left to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tuta disease (SMT), a group of inherited disorders that lead to nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that a misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with STDs because so little is known about the condition.
About 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have a STI that can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure gait and pinched toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she turned 18, and would die before she turned 30.
The mother of two, who is now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others could.
I fell every day, and I spent more time on everything.
I’ve never been able to ride rollerblades or skateboard with other kids, and I’ve been bullied a lot at school because of how I’ve been walking and running.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at the medical card when her doctor came out of the room, and it was written that she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I stuck my nose where I shouldn’t and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this state in the library and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and panicked as much as possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I turned 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in the meantime.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realized that her walking ability had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just got up, hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease because you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that poses a much smaller threat to your life.
After a few genetic tests, she was found to have an STD.
“When he explained what a SMT was, I thought I had pulled out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK’s SMT charity has announced a month of information about SMT to try to draw attention to this disease.
The tax burden on Washington-area entrepreneurs is on the rise as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
Accounts for state and local taxes for companies across the country rose moderately last year as the recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid out $27.6 billion in state and local cash in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on business by state and local level increased by 4.3 percent to $671 billion last year, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after the year-over-year declines in 2009 and 2010.
Taxes charged by the state grew faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county’s tax revenue, 56 percent, is corporate income tax, while 36 percent of Maryland’s tax revenue is corporate income.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, the rise in tax revenues is caused by a return to the previous level of real estate value of companies, the researchers say, which raised real estate taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row, when growth was less than 1 percent.
While much of this revenue comes from large states such as California, New York, and Texas, it seems the same is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012, up 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate value has no similar effect on the growth of state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies’ tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a non-profit organization that doesn’t pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center for State Taxation.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more on, for example, income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs’ incomes also seem to be going up, according to these data.
Companies in the region have declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
While trends are moving in one direction, the tax burden on entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three areas.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average of 4.3 per cent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, at 4.9 per cent.
Only in Virginia, there was a rise in tax revenues below the average of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax in three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the county it is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that in Virginia, taxes for entrepreneurs are lower by state and local level and, overall, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than in Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed legislation that reduced the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, as in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to as high as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be feeling better and thus paying more taxes by state and local level, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs paid in the form of an individual income tax by small business owners - the transitional structure on which most of the small firms - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia grew by 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much higher rate of growth than the previous year.
The researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country are likely to continue this year, with revenue from state and local government turnover tax revenues rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind, as a reduction in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
