The deputies proposed to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The State Duma has introduced a draft law providing for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is based on the legislative activities of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Just Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more rapid and effective protection of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and the observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, the entry into force of which parliamentarians are in a hurry, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed through the Internet.
It also makes it mandatory to record, systematize, accumulate, store, refine and extract personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as to indicate the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right, on the basis of a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called “blacklists” of offending websites – an automated information system “Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects”.
This law was passed by the state Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoy and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the CPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current draft law on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia, will have to pay for the rent
Commenting on the bill introduced today in the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he does not see any problems in transferring the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own stores of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom", which has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers for rent and already provides their servers, from Mail Group, their servers.
“In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
“If the companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problems – they will get technological opportunities for accommodation,” Levin said.
Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is passed, Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services of airline tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the draft law deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located in the territory of the Russian Federation."
The statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, systematization of his personal data.
In this case, you will be able to choose in which territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar laws on the “localization” of personal data in other countries has led to the loss of global services and significant economic losses.
