The saving certificate will make the name and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates on the bearer, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will prohibit savings certificates on the bearer.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that the savings certificates for the depositor do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and the bank they are cheaper, since it is not necessary to make deductions to the Fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (PAA).
The plight of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and Bank of Moscow will suffer from it, which, according to ASV estimates, control 98% of the profile market.
And the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in ASV, is that the customers of a small bank that bought such a certificate, in case of withdrawal from it, the licenses are trying to get money in ASV.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates on the bearer, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified lack of insurance payments on these certificates in case of revocation of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency there were cases when the holders of presentation certificates tried to collect insurance compensation through the court,” – said in the ASV.
The problem, of course, is imaginary.
After all, no one will pay buyers of certificates anyway, because they do not have the right by law to reimbursement from the state.
If the issue was that the instrument was not insured in ASV, it would also prohibit metal accounts, in which the citizens' funds are accounted for in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the system of deposit insurance, but their existence is not attempted.
The thing, most likely, is that the certificates on the bearer are a very convenient security, which can actually act as a quasi-deneg.
At the same time, their movement is virtually uncontrollable: any customer of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no accident that the draft law stipulates that a savings certificate must be an exact security, which must be stored in the depository.
And to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of the irrevocable contribution that bankers have long dreamed of.
