This feature allows you to make a payment at the cashier of the store using a smartphone.
The payment will be identified by the user by his fingerprint using the Touch ID function.
It is reported that the iPhone will for the first time incorporate NFC (near field communication) technology, which allows you to make a contactless payment using a smartphone and a corresponding reading device at the checkout.
NFC technology itself will be available thanks to a special microprocessor from the Dutch high-tech company NXP (formerly Philips Semiconductors).
The NFC feature was first introduced in 2004 as part of a collaboration between Sony, Nokia, Philips Semiconductors and more than a hundred other companies that have joined the so-called NFC Forum - the association for the promotion of this technology.
The first NFC phone was released by Nokia in 2006.
The first NFC-enabled Android smartphone, the Samsung Nexus S, was introduced in 2010.
In May 2011, Google introduced the Google Wallet system, which allows users to link bank cards to their Google account and pay using a smartphone on Android.
However, U.S. experts emphasize that despite the large investments of high-tech companies in the advancement of NFC technology, U.S. retailers are still cautious about innovation and are not too willing to spend money on the equipment of their stores with such systems.
