A massive hack of star accounts may have been made through a vulnerability in the Find My Phone app.
A potential scenario for the development of events was described by the resource The Next Web.
On Github, a Python script was published, which allowed you to select passwords to Apple's Find My Phone service.
This service allows you to track the location of the iPhone.
To access it, the same connection of the login and the Apple ID password is used as to access the Apple iCloud cloud, from which photos of celebrities were stolen.
The script allowed you to know the password from Find My Phone.
In this method, all sorts of combinations of symbols are consistently entered, starting with the most commonly used passwords.
The author of the script claimed that the number of password options entered in the Find My Phone service is unlimited.
With the correct organization of the security system after several unsuccessful attempts to enter the wrong password, the account should be blocked and notify the user of the attempted hack.
Due to the vulnerability, users did not receive any messages about trying to pick up the password to their account.
The hackers learned the password from Apple ID and used it to access iCloud.
According to a Hackapp user’s Twitter post, the vulnerability was discovered two days ago, on Saturday, and a password-selection scripting program was written to it.
At the moment, the vulnerability is closed: after five attempts, access to the service is blocked.
The resource contacted the Hackapp user and he noted that the above-mentioned vulnerability is characteristic of many services, but noted that there is no evidence that this vulnerability was used to access the "stars" account.
