SKR stopped the investigation of the Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (ICRC) has stopped criminal proceedings on the fact of the crash of the aircraft Tu-204 of the airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
The forensic examination showed that the cause of the crash was the increased speed of boarding, the failure of the crew to perform standard procedures on landing, as well as the unintentional output of the engines for increased direct thrust.
The Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings airline, which followed the flight from Prague to Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at the Moscow airport Vnukovo.
The aircraft rolled out of the runway and caught fire.
At the scene of the accident, the commander of the aircraft, the second pilot and the flight engineer were killed.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical facilities, where they subsequently died from injuries sustained.
Three other flight attendants, hospitalized with severe physical injuries, were undergoing long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, who was driving at the time of the accident on the Kiev highway, suffered serious bodily injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor's office after the accident carried out a check at the Red Wings, during which numerous violations were detected.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
