Anger is the most universal and functional emotion of man.
The angry facial expression is biologically universal to humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the United States have found.
They told about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly read about them in the press release of the University of California, Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - the slanted and lowered down eyebrows, stretched into a thin line of the lips, swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and is made even by children who are blind from birth, who have never seen it, notes the lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, the scientists found that this emotion arose for the effective conduct of disputes during the conflict.
The more physical damage one person can do to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he brings it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers found confirmations of another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to become angry and go hand-in-hand, consider themselves entitled to impose conditions unfavorable to others, and prefer forceful methods of conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Relying on the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining,” the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create the angry expression of the face should represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor – and thus force the conflict to agree with him as soon as possible.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled a person on a computer where each of the seven elements of an angry person was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or the forward chin individually did not make the face evil, the physically stronger person depicted with such features was unanimously recognized by the study participants.
The anger of man, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own strength, forcing one to consent and obey.
A person inflates the nostrils and squeezes the lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or baboon that demonstrates its claws.
Anger is “started” by the interlocutor’s refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that most effectively demonstrates the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry person are arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tubby.
The Ministry of Communications offered to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV-radio company "Crimea"
In 2014, the Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradiocompany "Crimea".
This is stated in the draft resolution of the government, prepared by the agency, which became acquainted with "Lenta.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed “to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and development of the modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment”.
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to be converted into hardware and studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state broadcaster "Crimea" was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the TV-radio company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Teleradio Company "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
